{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18542"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"10896"},{"type":"tags","id":"10902"},{"type":"tags","id":"10903"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENematodes (roundworms) represent a diverse phylum of animals that includes both free-living species and parasites of plants and animals. They have distinct anatomical features that separate them from other worm phyla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the fundamental anatomical characteristics of nematodes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ribbon-like body with ciliated epidermis","Flattened body with incomplete digestive system","Segmented body with setae and parapodia","Dorso-ventrally flattened body with proboscis","Cylindrical unsegmented body with complete digestive system"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defining characteristic of nematodes is their \u003Cstrong\u003Ecylindrical unsegmented body with complete digestive system\u003C/strong\u003E. They have a tube-within-a-tube body plan, with an outer body wall surrounding a fluid-filled pseudocoelom that contains the digestive tract and other organs. The digestive system is complete with both mouth and anus.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlattened body with incomplete digestive system\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes platyhelminthes (flatworms) which lack an anus\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESegmented body with setae and parapodia\u003C/strong\u003E - These are characteristics of annelids (segmented worms)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERibbon-like body with ciliated epidermis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes nemerteans (ribbon worms)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorso-ventrally flattened body with proboscis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of some flatworms, not nematodes\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EAdditional key features of nematodes include bilateral symmetry, a protective cuticle that is periodically shed during growth, and a pseudocoelom that functions as a hydrostatic skeleton.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nematodes are cylindrical, unsegmented worms with a complete digestive system and body cavity.","Nematodes have bilateral symmetry and are covered by a tough, protective cuticle that must be periodically shed.","The basic body plan of nematodes includes a pseudocoelom filled with fluid that acts as a hydrostatic skeleton."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61125"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18542"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61125"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T12:32:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T12:33:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4941"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024